===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Originally an {{liushu|i|nocap=y}}: an arrow 矢 with a distinguishing mark (now {{zh-l|*日}}). 

{{zh-ref|Chen (2019)}} considers it the original character of {{zh-l|*演|to advance; to stretch}}.

In the modern form the arrowhead has corrupted into {{zh-l|*宀}}.

===Etymology===
; 3rd earthly branch
: {{zh-ref|Smith (2011)}} suggests that this branch denoted the "bending, stretching, drawn out" moon phase, i.e. the waning half-moon with a concave flat edge. Smith points to
:*the possible relation between {{och-l|寅|id=2}} and {{och-l|引|id=1|to stretch, to draw (a bow)}} (noted earlier by {{w|James Mellon Menzies}}); and
:*that both graphs 寅 and 引 were used interchangeably as phonophorics for {{och-l|螾}} and {{och-l|蚓}}, meaning "worm".
: Association with the tiger was possibly arbitrary, just like {{zh-l|辰}} with the dragon (see {{zh-ref|Ferlus, 2013}})

